---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SidebarLayout from '../../components/shared/SidebarLayout.astro';

import { surgeryNavItems as navItems } from '../../data/surgeryNavItems';
---

<Layout description="Oral cancer screening and pathology services in Windsor, ON. Early detection of suspicious lesions, lumps, and sores. Contact Great Lakes Oral Surgery today."
  title="Oral Pathology - Great Lakes Oral & Maxillofacial Surgery Centre">
  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">{JSON.stringify({ "@context": "https://schema.org", "@graph": [
    { "@type": "MedicalWebPage", "name": "Oral Pathology & Oral Cancer Screening", "url": "https://www.greatlakessurgerycentre.com/surgery/oral-pathology", "description": "Oral cancer screening and biopsy services in Windsor, Ontario. Early detection of suspicious lesions, lumps, and sores.", "specialty": "Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery" },
    { "@type": "MedicalProcedure", "name": "Oral Pathology Biopsy", "procedureType": "Diagnostic", "bodyLocation": "Mouth, oral cavity", "description": "Evaluation and biopsy of suspicious oral lesions. Tissue is sent to a pathologist for identification. Early detection of oral cancer is critical.", "indication": "Reddish or whitish patches in the mouth; sores that fail to heal and bleed easily; lumps or thickening on the oral lining; chronic sore throat or hoarseness; difficulty chewing or swallowing." },
    { "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What are warning signs of oral cancer?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Warning signs include reddish patches (erythroplasia) or whitish patches (leukoplakia) in the mouth, a sore that fails to heal and bleeds easily, a lump or thickening on the skin lining the inside of the mouth, chronic sore throat or hoarseness, and difficulty chewing or swallowing. These changes can appear on the lips, cheeks, palate, gum tissue, tongue, face, or neck." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is a biopsy for oral pathology?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Larger or suspicious lesions require a biopsy. The tissue is anesthetized locally or with sedation, a piece of the tissue is removed, placed in tissue preservation, and sent to a lab where a pathologist identifies it under a microscope. We recommend monthly oral cancer self-examinations." } }
    ]}
  ]})}</script>
  <SidebarLayout title="Our Procedures" navItems={navItems} currentPath={Astro.url.pathname} eyebrow="Surgical Procedures" heroSubtitle="Expert oral and maxillofacial surgical procedures performed with precision and care.">
    <Fragment slot="card-header">
      <h2>Oral Pathology</h2>
      <p>Any alteration in the normal appearance of your mouth could be a warning sign for a pathological process. Do not ignore suspicious lumps or sores — early detection is critical.</p>
    </Fragment>

    <div class="leading-relaxed" style="color: #515151">
      <p class="mb-4">The inside of the mouth is normally lined with a special type of skin (mucosa) that is smooth and coral pink in color. Any alteration in this appearance could be a warning sign for a pathological process. The most serious of these is oral cancer. The following can be signs at the beginning of a pathologic process or cancerous growth:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mb-4 space-y-1">
        <li>Reddish patches (erythroplasia) or whitish patches (leukoplakia) in the mouth</li>
        <li>A sore that fails to heal and bleeds easily</li>
        <li>A lump or thickening on the skin lining the inside of the mouth</li>
        <li>Chronic sore throat or hoarseness</li>
        <li>Difficulty in chewing or swallowing</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mb-4">These changes can be detected on the lips, cheeks, palate and gum tissue around the teeth, tongue, face and/or neck. Pain does not always occur with pathology. However, any patient with facial and/or oral pain without an obvious cause or reason may also be at risk for oral cancer. We would recommend performing an oral cancer self-examination monthly and remember that your mouth is one of your body's most important warning systems. Do not ignore suspicious lumps or sores. Please contact us so we may help.</p>
      <p>Larger or more suspicious lesions require investigation by obtaining a piece of the tissue in question. This is traditionally known as a biopsy. The tissue abnormality will need to be anesthetized either locally, or in conjunction with some type of sedative technique. It is then placed in a jar of tissue preservation and sent to a lab where a pathologist will identify it under a microscope.</p>
    </div>
  </SidebarLayout>
</Layout>
